B

BAR - Class in GP.MutationOperators
The Boolean and Relational (BAR) mutation combines the functionality of both the BER and BEM mutations, with the mutation being able to; switch boolean and relational operators of expressions, add and remove negation to child expressions and remove parts of expressions also.
BAR() - Constructor for class GP.MutationOperators.BAR
 
BEM - Class in GP.MutationOperators
The Boolean Expression Modification (BEM) mutation is a child of the Boolean And Relational (BAR) mutation, with the goal of switching the boolean and relational operators of expressions
and adding and removing negation to child expressions.

Expressions found in if, while and ternary statements are collected with boolean variables and fields and boolean return types collected also.
BEM() - Constructor for class GP.MutationOperators.BEM
 
BER - Class in GP.MutationOperators
The BER mutation provides the functionality of both the BER Expansion and BER Reduction mutations combined, with the end goal of this mutation to be able to add too and remove expressions found in the program.
BER() - Constructor for class GP.MutationOperators.BER
 
BERExpansion - Class in GP.MutationOperators
The BER Expansion mutation is a child of the Boolean Expansion and Reduction mutation, with the goal of adding to boolean expressions in the program.
Expressions found in if, while and ternary statements are collected with boolean variables and fields and boolean return types collected also.
BERExpansion() - Constructor for class GP.MutationOperators.BERExpansion
 
BERReduction - Class in GP.MutationOperators
The BER Reduction mutation is a child of the Boolean Expansion and Reduction mutation, with the goal of reducing compound boolean expressions in the program.
Binary expressions in: if, while and for loops can be collected with boolean variables and fields and boolean return types collected also.
BERReduction() - Constructor for class GP.MutationOperators.BERReduction

GNR - Class in GP.MutationOperators
The Generate Node Replacement (GNR) mutation is a fairly diverse mutation with many possible outcomes, entry points to the program which consist of variable declarations, field access expression, object creation expressions and method call expressions are collected.

Their values are replaced with a node that is generated from the nodes available to the entry point in the local and limited global scope.
GNR() - Constructor for class GP.MutationOperators.GNR

L

LRR - Class in GP.MutationOperators
The Line Removal and Relocation (LRR) mutation combines the functionality of both the LRRelocation and LRRemoval mutations, with the mutation being able to;
move statements in the same method around, and remove specific nodes in the program as a whole around too.
LRR() - Constructor for class GP.MutationOperators.LRR
 
LRRelocation - Class in GP.MutationOperators
The LRRelocation mutation is a child of the Line Relocation and Removal (LRR) mutation, with the goal of moving statements in the same method around.
Variable declarations, method calls, if, while, do-while, for, try and switch statements, and throw statements can all be moved.
LRRelocation() - Constructor for class GP.MutationOperators.LRRelocation
 
LRRemoval - Class in GP.MutationOperators
The LRRemoval mutation is a child of the Line Removal and Relocation (LRR) mutation, with the goal of removing statements.
These include, if, while, do-while, for, try and switch statements, methods calls, variable declarations, throw, break, continue and return keywords.
LRRemoval() - Constructor for class GP.MutationOperators.LRRemoval

mutate(CompilationUnit) - Static method in class GP.MutationOperators.BAR
(1) Determine which mutation to choose from, 50/50 for either Boolean Expression Manipulation (BEM) or Boolean expansion and reduction (BER) mutation
(2) Run the mutation and return the modified program back
mutate(CompilationUnit) - Static method in class GP.MutationOperators.BEM
(1) Boolean expressions in the program are collected, for example (x > 5 && y > 5)
(2) If a valid expression could not be found then return the program unmodified
(3) A random expression from the list of available expressions is chosen and different actions are taken depending on the instance type
(4) If the expression is a Unary expression then remove the unary expression and get the expression inside
(5) If the expression is a Binary expression then the mutation has two options
 (5.1) 50% chance to modify the binary expressions operator
  (5.1.1) Generally, if the current operator of the expression is a boolean operator (&&, ||) then a random boolean operator is chosen
  (5.1.2) Generally, if the current operator of the expression is a relational operator (!=, <=, ...) then a random relational operator is chosen
  (5.1.3) If the binary expression is a string then .equals() is used for the relational operator and if a boolean then the relational operators are limited to == and !=
 (5.2) 50% chance to enclose the expression in a negation operator
(6) If the expression is a BooleanLiteralExpr e.g.
mutate(CompilationUnit) - Static method in class GP.MutationOperators.BER
(1) Determine which mutation to choose from, 50/50 for either BER Expansion or BER Reduction
(2) Run the mutation and return the modified program back
mutate(CompilationUnit) - Static method in class GP.MutationOperators.BERExpansion
(1) Boolean expressions are collected in the program for example: (x > 5 && y > 5)
(2) If no expressions where found then the original program is returned unmodified
(3) A random expression from the program is split into child nodes in the example above these would be: x > 5, y > 5
(4) A child is picked at random such as the child: x > 5 and a 50/50 decision is made whether to add a new expression to the left or right side of this child
(5) Determine what expression to add: single expression with and without negation or a binary expression
(6) There is a 25% chance that a single expression of type binary will be added to the child from the local or global scope
(7) There is a 25% chance that a single expression of type binary with negation will be added to the child from the local or global scope
(8) There is a 50% chance that a binary expression will be added to the program
 (8.1) All types in the local/global scope of the child are collected and types with less than two nodes are discarded
 (8.2) A random type is chosen if the number of valid types is greater than zero, if not then the program is returned unmodified
 (8.3) Two nodes with the same type are set as the left and right nodes of the binary expression
 (8.4) The relational operator is randomised, if the type of node is boolean then only == and != are selected and if the type is String then a random string comparison method such as; .equals() or .startsWith() is used for comparison
(9) Now that a new expression has been formed a random boolean operator is selected to join the expression and child and the original expression is updated
mutate(CompilationUnit) - Static method in class GP.MutationOperators.BERReduction
(1) Binary expression parents are collected in the program, for example (x > 5 && y > 5 && z > 5) is a binary expr parent, where (y > 5 && z > 5) is a binary expression child and is not collected
(2) If a valid expression could not be found then return the program unmodified
(3) The parent binary expression is split into child nodes in the example above these would be: x > 5, y > 5 and z > 5
(4) A child is picked at random such as the child: x > 5
(5) If the parent to the child is a binary expression then the siblings of the child are collected through the parent and the child node is removed
(6) If the child is wrapped in a unary, ! or enclosed expression, () then the binary expression of the child is found and the same process as step five is applied
mutate(CompilationUnit) - Static method in class GP.MutationOperators.GNR
(1) Entry point collection takes place, meaning variable declarations, field access expressions, method call expressions and object creation expressions in the program are collected
(2) If no allowed nodes in the program where found then the program is returned unmodified
(3) Otherwise a different action is performed based on the node instance
 (3.1) If the node is a variable declarator then the variable initialiser (e.g.
mutate(CompilationUnit) - Static method in class GP.MutationOperators.LRR
(1) Determine which mutation to choose from, 50/50 for either LRRelocation or LRRemoval
(2) Run the mutation and return the modified program back
mutate(CompilationUnit) - Static method in class GP.MutationOperators.LRRelocation
(1) Collect from the program all nodes that are specified in the LRR 'getAllowedNodes()' method, for this mutation this list is modified by the mutation to remove Switch entries, Field declarations and a few others
(2) Two unique nodes are selected from the program that comply to the allowed nodes, if two unique nodes cannot be found then the program is returned unmodified
(3) The second node with the name of 'nodeTo' which is the location nodeFrom will relocate to, does not have a block statement ancestor then the program is returned as the mutation requires a block statement for relocation
(4) NodeFrom is copied above nodeTo using the 'addBefore()' method that BlockStmt provides, and the original nodeFrom is removed
(5) The modified program is then returned
mutate(CompilationUnit) - Static method in class GP.MutationOperators.LRRemoval
(1) Collect from the program all nodes that are specified in the LRR 'getAllowedNodes()' method
(2) If a valid node could not be found then return the program unmodified
(3) Pick a random node from the list of available nodes.
